You need a list of the reasons why BASIC is not powerful enough as a language?

Let me count (some of) the ways:

1)  No indefinite extent.  (Live objects/data structures can't live between "program"
invocations.)

2)  No first class citizens.  (All objects of the language *should* be able to
participate in *all* activities sanctioned by the language.  If you can put integers
in arrays, you must also be able to put arrays in arrays, functions in arrays, or
any other data type.)

3)  No higher order functions.  (Functions can't be returned as results from other
functions, nor can they be passed as arguments to other functions.)

4)  No (dynamic) lists.

5)  No garbage collection.

6)  While typing isn't as strict as Pascal, it's still not as permissive as a
latently typed language (where types matter *only* at the moment of function
application--until then any type can be passed to any formal parameter).

7)  You can't have locally defined functions.  (Functions defined inside of
other functions.)

8)  You can't have anonymous functions.  (All functions must be named.)

9)  Inconsistent syntax for commands versus functions (and indeed, for some
commands versus other commands).  You lose a lot by not having IF be a true
function for instance.

10)  No macros.

11)  No short circuit and/or.

12)  You can't arbitrarily split code up on different lines (no coherent
mechanism for determining where functions begin/end).  This means you have
to cram things on the same line (how unreadable) and you can easily be
up against line size limits.  Even goofy line continuation character
approaches are a dreadful kludge here.

Is this enough or do you want more???

[snip]

