I beg to differ:  I claim it is by no means the unquestioned language of
choice.  In fact, I'd say the opposite:  it's an unquestioned loser as far
as languages go.

The only way for BASIC to come close to the power of LISP is to become
LISP (and then it wouldn't be BASIC anymore, if you follow the way I've
drifted here ;-) .

My vote is clearly for LISP as the ultimate general purpose programming
language.

If people understood it, BASIC would not be...as it is, BASIC seems doomed
to reinvent LISP wheels.

If we had Visual LISP instead of Visual BASIC, the OO stuff would be moot:
you'd have all the power you need to roll your own objects as you like.

Maybe someday the LISP community will get a marketing department.

Oh well, such is life...

